        <h1>LeetCode 1925: Count Square Sum Triples (C++)</h1>
        <div class="problem-description">
            <p><strong>Problem:</strong>
                A square triple (a, b, c) is a triple where a, b, and c are integers and a² + b² = c². Given an integer
                n,
                return the number of square triples such that 1 <= a, b, c <=n. The solution uses a two-pointer approach
                    for each possible value of c, searching for pairs (a, b) where a² + b²=c². We count both (a, b, c)
                    and (b, a, c) as distinct triples unless a=b. </p>
                    <p><strong>Example:</strong>
                        Input: n = 5 → Output: 2. The square triples are (3,4,5) and (4,3,5), so count is 2.
                        Input: n = 10 → Output: 4. Valid triples include (3,4,5), (4,3,5), (6,8,10), (8,6,10).
                        Input: n = 2 → Output: 0. No valid square triples exist with all values ≤ 2.
                    </p>
        </div>
        <div class="code-container">
            <button class="copy-button" onclick="copyCode(this)">Copy Code</button>
            <pre><code class="language-cpp">class Solution {
public:
    int countTriples(int n) {
        int ans = 0;
        for (int c = 1; c &lt;= n; ++c) {
            long long target = 1LL * c * c;
            int a = 1, b = c - 1;
            while (a &lt;= b) {
                long long s = 1LL * a * a + 1LL * b * b;
                if (s == target) {
                    if (a == b)
                        ans += 1;      // (a,a,c) only one order
                    else
                        ans += 2;      // (a,b,c) and (b,a,c)
                    ++a;
                    --b;
                }
                else if (s &lt; target) {
                    ++a;
                }
                else {
                    --b;
                }
            }
        }
        return ans;
    }
};</code></pre>
